EDITABLE CODE 
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________	
We (Britzman and Mehic-Parker, 2022) relied on Gregg & Sedikides, 2010 implicit self-esteem code to build the template for ambivalent sexism. 

check below for (relatively) easily editable parameters, stimuli, instructions etc. 
Keep in mind that you can use this script as a template and therefore always "mess" with the entire code 
to further customize your experiment.

The parameters you can change are:

/responsetimeout1_signal:		stores the longest response timeouts in ms used in this study for targets
								Note: by default, the longest response timeout in this script is used for blocks
								that test attributes and targets separately (default: 1000ms)
								
/responsetimeout2_signal


/responsetimeout3_signal
													
(samefor noise trials: by default they are the same in this script)

/isi:							stores the interstimulus interval (time between offset of one stimulus and onset of next)
											


</usermanual>


**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************
	EDITABLE PARAMETERS: change editable parameters here
**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************

<parameters>
/responsetimeout1_signal = 1000
/responsetimeout2_signal = 750
/responsetimeout3_signal = 600

/responsetimeout1_noise = 1000
/responsetimeout2_noise = 750
/responsetimeout3_noise = 600

/isi = 500
</parameters>

**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************
	EDITABLE STIMULI: change editable stimuli here
**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************

<item targetAlabel>
/ 1 = "Woman"
</item>

<item TargetA>
/ 1 = "Female"
/ 2 = "Girl"
</item>

<item NoiseA>
/1 = "Male"
/2 = "Boy"
</item>

<item targetBlabel>
/1 = "Man"
</item>

<item TargetB>
/1 = "Male"
/2 = "Boy"
</item>

<item NoiseB>
/1 = "Woman"
/2 = "Girl"
</item>

<item attributeAlabel>
/1 = "Occupations"
</item>

<item attributeA>
/1 = "Doctor" 
/2 = "Nurse"
/3 = "Lawyer"
/4 = "Teacher"
/5 = "Scientist"
/6 = "Social worker"
/7 = "Police officer"
/8 = "Engineer"
/9 = "Administrative assistant" 
/10 = "Secretary"
/11 = "Manager"
/12 = "Cashier" 
/13 = "Retail salesperson"
</item>


<item attributeBlabel>
/ 1 = "Attributes"
</item>

<item attributeB>
/ 1 = "Seek special favors" 
/ 2 = "Overreact"
/ 3 = "More cultured" 
/ 4 = "More honorable" 
/ 5 = "Overly emotional" 
/ 6 = "Too sensitive" 
/ 7 = "Make partner complete"
/ 8 = "More moral"
/ 9 = "Easily offended"
/ 10 = "Exaggerate problems"
/ 11 = "Make demands"
/ 12 = "Pure"
/ 13 = "Worth sacrifices" 
/ 14 = "Idolized"
/ 15 = "Want power"
/ 16 = "Worth cherishing" 
/ 17 = "Worth protecting" 
/ 18 = "Unreasonable"
</item>


**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************
	EDITABLE INSTRUCTIONS: change instructions here
**************************************************************************************************************
**************************************************************************************************************
<instruct>
/ wait = 1000 
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3.0%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
</instruct>


<surveypage intro1>
/ caption = "

Please read the instructions carefully before proceeding with the task.
~n~nThis research investigates cognitive processes that are used in decisions that involve memory. We are seeking to develop and test theories of the cognitive processes that occur outside of awareness in the routine use of memory. Stimuli for the category task will be presented on this display screen, and your responses will be entered <%expressions.buttoninstruct2%>. 
~n~nYou will have an opportunity to practice before your responses are recorded."
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ txcolor = white
/ showpagenumbers = false
/ showquestionnumbers = false
</surveypage>

<surveypage intro2>
/ caption = "
This task assumes that you can read English fluently, and that your vision is normal or corrected to normal.
~nThe tasks that you will be doing in this experiment involve category judgment. For instance, in one condition your task may be to search for all the words that represent the categories 'attributes' (e.g., pure) or the category 'woman' (e.g., female).
~n~nAll categorizations will be made with the space bar <%expressions.buttoninstruct1%>.  When you see a word that belongs to one of the categories (e.g., 'woman' or 'attributes') hit the space bar <%expressions.buttoninstruct1%> as fast as possible. 
~n~nIgnore words that do not belong to either category."
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ txcolor = white
/ showpagenumbers = false
/ showquestionnumbers = false
</surveypage>

<surveypage intro3>
/ caption = "
The words you will be looking for will be from the 4 groups listed below.
~nWomen (white letters): female, girl
~nMen (white letters): male, boy
~nOccupations (blue letters) that people have. These occupations are any jobs or careers that people might have throughout their lives. Examples include: Doctor, nurse, lawyer, or retail salesperson
~nAttributes (blue letters) that people possess. These attributes are any qualities or traits that may describe a person or people or behaviors that they might exhibit. Examples include: Unreasonable, pure, easily offended, worth sacrifices
~nFor example, any occupation included in the list or any attribute that a person has could be in those categories. The color coding of the words will help distinguish between the categories."
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ txcolor = white
/ showpagenumbers = false
/ showquestionnumbers = false
</surveypage>

**^Changed qualities to attributes and added definitions for both attributes and occupations**


<surveypage intro4>
/ caption = "
The task is fast-paced and hard. In fact, you may at times find it very difficult to  correctly classify ANY of the trials.  
~nThis task is designed to be difficult and no one is expected to perform it perfectly. Please persevere and just try to catch as many words as possible.
~nYou will have an opportunity to practice before the task begins.
~n~nWe will start now with a training procedure to get you familiarized with the four categories and stimuli used in this task.
There will be a training block for each of the four categories. The computer will alert you when the categories change.
~nHit START when you are ready to start the training."
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 3%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ txcolor = white
/ showpagenumbers = false
/ showquestionnumbers = false
</surveypage>


<page end>
You have reached the end of the task. You will now be returned to Qualtrics to complete the survey.
^^Thank you!
</page>

**^ Added language stating that participants will be routed back to the survey**

<item reminders>
/ 1 = "Let's start the categorization task
~n~nWords will appear in the center of the screen, one by one, at high speed. These words may or may not belong to the category you see printed at the top.
~nPress the space bar as fast as you can if the word belongs to the category you see at the top. If they do not belong to the category, don't do anything. Just wait for the next word.
~nIf you made an error, a red X appears below the word. Otherwise, you will see a green 'O'.
~n~n~nPress the space bar to start practice trials."
/ 2 = "New category - Press the space bar for practice trials"
/ 3 = "The set-up has changed. Instead of only one category, you now see TWO categories printed at the top.
~nPress the space bar as fast as you can if the word appearing in the center belongs to EITHER one of the two categories you see at the top. Don't do anything if the word does not belong to either one of the categories.
~n~n~nPress the space bar for practice trials."
/ 4 = "New categories - Press the space bar for practice trials"
</item>

<text trainingEnd>
/ items = ("The training session has ended.
~n~nPress the space bar to continue.")
/ position = (50%, 65%) 
/ size = (60%, 50%)
/ txcolor = white 
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 2.67%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ vjustify = center
/ hjustify = center
</text>


<text testTrialReminder1>
/ items = ("You are now starting main trial 1 of 4
~nPress the space bar as fast as you can if the word appearing in the center belongs to EITHER or BOTH of the 2 categories you see at the top.
~n~n~nPress the space bar to start.")
/ position = (50%, 65%) 
/ size = (60%, 50%)
/ txcolor = white 
/ fontstyle = ("Arial", 2.67%, false, false, false, false, 5, 1)
/ vjustify = center
/ hjustify = center
</text>

